animal.description:
Howdy from Waynesboro MS!! I'm MISSY!! I'm just a young southern gal ing for a loving home!! 
I've been looking for love in all the wrong places!

NATURE
Other dogs: loves playing with others
Cats: curious about them but very little exposure
Kids: loves but can knock down small one
Adults: love attention, very energetic
Additional comments 

TRAINING
House broke: No but she doesn't mess up her kennel
Pad trained: only exposed to pads after spayed. She did well. 

Leash trained: Yes but also loves to run free

VACCINATIONS
UTD 
SPAYED

This sweet carefree girl has been living at a very rural shelter in Mississippi with not lots of chance of being adopted. We offered to help her find a loving forever home here in WI. She will need some direction on her house manners but is clearly a very sweet smart girl who loves to please. If interested in this sweetheart an online application can be found at SandiPaws.org

She had an owner but sadly her owner went off to school and had no one to watch her so she went to the shelter. Sissy took it hard for a bit but is now back to being her silly happy self. She loves people and loves attention the most. She does well with other dogs with no issues and walks pretty well on a leash. animal.description:
We can't wait for you to meet Rosie!

Rosie is an adorable pit bull terrier mix, aged 3 1/2 years old. Many may remember her from last summer. She was adopted, but recently returned.

She has a pretty red coat and perky ears! Rosie has the sweetest personality and you can tell how loyal she is just by looking at her eyes! 

Rosie has gained a touch of weight since she has been gone, but other than that, she is a happy, healthy girl. A home where she gets to be someone's special companion would suit this girl just fine!

Rosie tested negative for heart worms and is now receiving monthly preventatives for fleas, ticks, intestinal parasites and heart worms. She is also fully vaccinated and spayed. 

If you are interested in meeting Rosie, please call us at 580-252-7387 or send us a message on Facebook.For more information, please email Stephens County Humane Society at schs@att.net, or call us at 580-252-7387 (PETS). Our animals are spayed/neutered, UTD on shots, and treated for ticks, & fleas. Cats are tested for FeLV & FIV; and dogs are tested for heart worms.

Normal adoption fee for cats is $75.00; and $100.00 for dogs, but we frequently have specials running and/or animals who have had their adoption fee sponsored, so ... call us! Let us help you find your next fur-baby!

I have not met a person I didn't like and I do great with dog, horses and goats. I love car rides and chillin on the couch. I sits for a treat but if U toss it to me it is most likely going to hit me between the eyes and bounce away. Mom says this is cute too but I'm learning. I'll catch it one day soon.

I am a ready made dog. An adopters dream. Hurry cuz I won't last long!

animal.description:
Colorado bio: Balboa (Bo for short) is a low-maintenance, mature dog who loves to lay around and chill (and if you can be bothered for a belly rub life is even better). This gentle guy has good mannershe knows not to beg for food when his people are eating and he does not bark at passing cars or pedestrians. Though he is fine with lounging much of the day, he does enjoy getting out for short walks where he can see and interact with other dogs. He likes the snow too, and weve noticed that he picks up his pace in the cold. Bo is a great companion to have around as you work from home because hell rest near your desk and be quite content with an occasionally petting, treat, or belly rub. His calm, sweet demeanor suggests that this handsome guy (so well-dressed with his white tuxedo) would be good with children and other dogs.

Texas bio: Balboa is a very easy going, sweet, couch potato! He is happy to spend his time just chilling next to you on the couch, sometimes with his head in your lap. While in a new environment, you may notice a little separation anxiety until he gets settled in to his new home (as with many dogs). He appears to be house trained as he will let you know when he needs to go outside. He doesn't beg for human food at the table. He enjoys walks but likes to go at a leisurely pace. What does this mean? No pulling! He just walks along at a nice slow walking speed, with the occasional stop to sniff around. He's just an all-around good boy! 

 

Balboa is a love bug and an old soul, you can feel it when you're around him, he deserves someone very special.

 

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming

animal.description:
Hello! My name is Cassey, and I am the small package that good things come in! I may be tiny, but I have a big, adorable personality. I love to play with my 4 foster sisters and am learning to entertain myself (though I would much prefer to be around other dogs or people!). I dont know anything about cats or small humans, but Im sure I would love them (and of course they would love me!). When I get sleepy, I happily go put myself in the corner (or in your lap) for a nap. At first, I didnt understand why I had to potty outside, but as long as its not too cold, or I have friends outside to play with, I am getting better at something my foster parents call potty training. At nighttime, my foster parents put me in something they call a kennel, and its the perfect place for me to decompress, relax, and sleep. They even let me sleep in there all night, no interruptions. Its great! I am a little shy, so I hope you wont mind giving me a little bit of time to get to know you. I promise I am worth your time and patience. If youre looking for the perfect, small, and loving dog, I cant wait to meet you!

animal.description:
Hi, everybody! My names George and Im one of the happiest dogs youll ever meet. Im clearly a handsome guy, but my personality is my best quality. Im spunky, happy-go-lucky and super friendly with everyone other dogs included. I especially love being close to my foster mom, showing her affection with lots of licks and tail wags. Shes nicknamed me Curious George as I love following her around to see what shes up to.

 

Do you have lots of toys for me to play with? Squeaky ones are my favorite, and if theres one of those around, its usually in my mouth. I love going for walks and am good on a leash. Im also house-trained, although I dont enjoy being crated at night Id much rather cuddle with my foster mom (but she wont let me up in bed with her!).

 

At 40 pounds, Im the perfect size not too big, not too small, juuuuuust right! My best home would be one with lots of activity and kids, and other dogs would be fine, too. I have to warn you, though, Im an attention hog who always wants to get the most cuddles and pets from my humans. A yard would be great to play in so that I can chase the resident bunnies and squirrels.

 

If youre looking for a friendly, happy dog that just wants to give and receive love, please apply to adopt me. I cant wait to find my forever home and I hope its with you!

 

 

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming

01-26-21 UPDATE FROM THE FOSTER:

Handsome Jughead might be 10 years old but he has a young heart and feet. He is calm indoors and loves food toys. Outside he is active and has plenty of energy for long walks or running—he does well on the leash. He’s great with children and friendly toward other dogs. Jughead has that lovely hound bark but he uses it very rarely and only does single barks. He loves cuddles and affection and sleeps well through the night.
======================================================

Meet calm, sweet senior Jughead. This boy spent his whole life of ten years with one family as an elderly person’s companion. Sadly, she was moved to a nursing home and obviously couldn’t take him with her! Black and tan coonhound Jughead was heartbroken but has been nothing but sweet and kind to everyone in the shelter. He is a medium sized boy at 60 pounds that loves being petted and going for walks. He will probably greatly enjoy walks in his forever home but will also be a great couch potato companion. Looking for a family who understands hounds and really wants to help a senior dog live out his golden years on top! He will need decompression time and time to get used to his new family’s schedule and expectations. He is good with dogs, cats, and kids. He is not a jumpy dog which is great when there are younger kids around. To apply for Jughead please visit our website www.peace4paws.org and fill out an adoption application. Thank you!!

animal.description:
In December we received a call stating that due to Annie’s human having unforeseen health issues over the last several months, she is no longer able to care for or give her the attention she needs.  Wags to Riches quickly responded and Annie was placed into one of our amazing foster homes.  

SAY HELLO TO ANNIE…Annie is a 9 month old America Bully/Shepherd mix who currently weighs in at 57 pounds.  Annie, through no fault of her own, is a bit of a wild child and will need a human who is an experienced dog owner.  Annie needs a family who will invest time into her and her training needs.   Her Wags foster is currently working with a trainer to get her on the right track and we know that continuing this training after her adoption will be the key to Annie’s success in her new forever family!  Annie is a very smart girl who is eager to please.  She loves training as it gives her an outlet for her energy.  Annie is a fun, spunky gal who plays well with others.  She will thrive with an active family!
Here is a few more important things about Annie:

Personality:  She is described by her foster as a fun, playful girl who has a big personality and high energy. 

Uniqueness:  Her ears have a personality and mind of their own.  She has a gorgeous and soft grey coat with brown speckles and brindle throughout. 

Potty trained: YES- but does go out every 2-3 hours and once over the night.

Crate trained: YES- she sleeps in a kennel at night and during the day she has stayed in the kennel for up to 4 hours. 

Dogs: YES- she would be great with another dog her size and one that is playful to help Annie work off her energy.  NO to older, small or low energy dogs as Annie could be very overwhelming to them.

Cats:  NOT ADVISED- Due to Annie’s energy level and want to play a little rough/ puppy behaviors. 

Kids:  YES & NO- Due to Annie’s size and energy level at this time, we would advise children over the age of 8 years old with some knowledge of dogs.  Annie tries to be in charge and can push boundaries so younger kids would not be advised.
 
Miscellaneous: Annie loves car rides and currently is working on walking on a leash and basic commands.  She does get excited, pulls and gets distracted but she is a large size and still a puppy so her training will make a difference and is extremely important.   

As mentioned Annie has had minimal training to this point so her manners need work but the potential is there and with training, the sky is the limit for her!!!    It is important to remember that Annie is still a puppy (under a year old) and weighs in at almost 60 pounds so she will need strong, dedicated and consistent humans in her life.

If you think Annie may be the one for you, please go to our website at www.wagstorichesanimalrescue.org and fill out an application to adopt.  Please be sure to include a vet reference as regular vet care is important to us for the health of all our adopted dogs. With approval and a $295 adoption donation, she will be ready to accompany you on all of life’s many adventures.  Annie is spayed, microchipped, fecal tested clean of internal parasites and up to date on all her vaccinations.

Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

animal.description:
Meet Athena! This pretty Shepherd or Husky mix was surrendered by her owner to the rescue. He recently lost his home and car and was headed to another state and couldn't take her with him. He contacted our team for help right before he left town, giving us little time to plan for her arrival. Some of our team members in SC had worked with him in the past, rescuing 14 other dogs off his property that were being kept outside. They tried to secure Athena, but he wanted to keep her. Athena was fortunate to be an inside dog and considered part of his family, but he was by no means a responsible owner.

After a two-hour transport to safety, Athena was seen by one of our partner vets before she went to her new foster home. She's being fostered with two other dogs and has been respectful of them, but slow to warm up over the first week. We think she's the type of dog who needs a gradual introduction and time to build rapport, and trust her new environment. Her people skills are fantastic, and she connected with her foster mom right away. We think she would love to be an only dog getting all the attention, or best paired with a more laid back dog. She did live with cats in the past, so a cat home would work too.

Athena is an active dog who can be high-energy when it's playtime but enjoys relaxing on her dog bed. She enjoys going on walks and can play fetch all day! She does pull some on the leash, but leash walking is new to her and she's still learning. She isn't bothered by traffic or noises but likes to check out other people or dogs walking by.

Athena's foster mom, Hanna, describes her as a confident and snuggly pup. "She's not timid in new situations or fearful of noises and will enthusiastically greet you by jumping up to hug you with her front paws. She has great house manners, is potty trained, and took quickly to her crate. She is very friendly and social when meeting new people."

This fun and affectionate dog needs an active owner or family to take her on new adventures. Her social skills make her ideal for road trips and social outings with friends.

Athena will be coming to N. Va on 2/6/21. Apply today!

BREED ESTIMATE: Shepherd/Husky Mix
GENDER: Female
APPROXIMATE WEIGHT: 49 lbs
APPROXIMATE AGE: ~ 1 year old
COAT TYPE: Short
ADOPTION FEE: $400
OTHER INFO: utd on shots/spayed/microchipped/
LOCATION: York, SC

FOR MORE INFO OR TO ADOPT: Please go to https://adopt.worthydog.org and complete the application.

You can also help save dogs like this one by becoming a foster, providing a rescue dog with a temporary home and giving them the love and care they need until they are permanently adopted. Every person who fosters is directly responsible for saving the life of a dog, because we can only save as many dogs as we have foster families available to welcome them into their homes. If you think you might be interested in becoming a foster and want to learn more, please go to https://foster.worthydog.org and fill out an application.

Worthy Dog Rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue that primarily adopts to families in the DC Metro area.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Initially shy in her foster home, lovely Lady now feels happily at home there. Acting far younger than her seven years, she's best buddies with the resident dog, loves going on walks with him, and running and playing with him in the backyard. Very affectionate towards her fosters, she could cuddle with them all day on the couch, but when she senses an adventure's at hand, she's up and exploring the possibilities. Highly intelligent, she responds well to training and redirection, walks well on leash without pulling, yet remains fearful of cars passing by. Respectful of her feline foster friends' space, she's well mannered, free roams when alone and is fully housetrained. Now for lovable Lady to thrive, she needs patient adopters with a consistent routine who will introduce her slowly to their other dogs if applicable, and assure that she's not only adored but kept mentally and physically satisfied fur-ever.

Animal Rescue of the Rockies believes that every pet should find a wonderful, caring home. To ensure each pet finds the best possible home, we ask that you fill out our Adoption Application so we can learn more about you and your household. We review each application we receive and will contact you within 48 hours. If your home sounds like a good match for you and the pet,

the next step is to set up a "meet and greet." After meeting the pet, if you would like to proceed with adopting, we'll ask that you read and sign our Adoption Agreement and pay the adoption fee. Our adoption fees help cover the costs of saving more lives!

A home visit will be scheduled within one week of your new pet going home with you.

The adoption fee for this pet is $300. Our adoption fee covers the following:

- Spay/Neuter, Microchip

- DAPP vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for all DAPP boosters after adoption.

- Rabies vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for any rabies vaccinations after adoption.

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an adoption application by clicking

here

.

We want our pets to go to a lifelong new home, so thank you for your patience during the adoption process!

Please email ARRColorado@gmail.com for more information, as we can not accept calls at this time.

Our adoption process is:

1. Fill out our Adoption Application online. We'll contact you within 48 hours to answer any questions you may have about the pet.

2. If the pet looks like a great match, we'll schedule a meet and greet and ask you to fill out our online Adoption Agreement if you'd like to proceed with adopting. Once you've completed the Adoption Agreement and pay the pet's Adoption Fee, you can arrange to pick up your new furry family member!

animal.description:
MEET ROSCOE!!!!!

~Roscoe is 6 years old but still such a sweet little puppy! He's looking for a home as an only dog and no cats. He loves to snuggle and be glued to your side so hopefully a home where he's allowed on the couch! He adores kids (7 and up, only because of his size and excited wiggles) and just want to play and be close to them! So a family with or without kiddos would make him so happy either way! He sleeps next to the bed in his own dog bed and does sometimes sneak on the bed but overall does really well in his bed! Roscoe has a lot of energy so if you like to get out and walk or hike he's your man! He will need continued work on a leash but has had lots of training and does well. He's not much of a camper though, we think he doesn't like the dark very much, but day trips and car adventures he's ready for! He is kennel trained and also dog door trained. To start off I would work on kennel training then slowly build trust to roam and have access to a dog door. He needs tall fences and preferably not the metal see through ones. He currently has a dog run set up he can access at all times and then whole yard roam when someone is home. He loves to sun bathe and enjoy the patio. Roscoe loves his indestructi-bone, he could chew on that for hours! We will make sure he gets sent with his! Overall this boy is the sweetest and goofiest boy! He talks a lot, and if he's not apart of a conversation he will make it known that he has something to say! It cracks us up! He's a people dog and simply needs your snuggles and love to be happy!

If you would like to meet this dog, please visit our website for our adoption application, www.underdogaz.com or email info@underdogaz.com

animal.description:
Meet Taco Bell!

9-year-old Taco Bell entered Bonita Shelter as a stray. He did have a microchip, but sadly his owner failed to come forward. So, we made Taco Bell a Frosted Face on January 22nd! At the shelter, he didn't always like being handled, which isn't unusual under these circumstances. and it makes Taco Bell the perfect candidate for a two-week Frosted Fling.

For the next two weeks, Taco Bell gets to decompress in a home environment. We won't be surprised if Taco Bell becomes much more comfortable being picked up and handled. His Fling Mom reports that he is already playing fetch and nudging her when he wants to be petted. Be sure to watch the videos to see how adorable Taco Bell is!

Check back soon for the next update on Taco Bell!

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Apply to become a family: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

animal.description:
Update!
RJ had his enucleation surgery and is so much happier. He's even more playful and affectionate than he was before the surgery. He's a really terrific boy who is lovable, brave, resilient and so smart!
RJ is a seven year old Dutch Shepherd mix. He was found wandering on the mean streets of South Los Angeles by himself, and taken to a high kill shelter. We pulled RJ out of the shelter to give him a chance at a good life. RJ has PRA (Progressive Retinal Atrophy) and cataracts and is blind. He doesn't let the lack of sight affect his quality of life, and is a happy guy who finds his way around just fine. This brave boy is only hesitant about one thing: traffic noises.
RJ has a surgery coming up to remove both eyes because he has blown up a case of glaucoma in both eyes. He will be much happier, and pain free afterwards. He'll be available for adoption as soon as he is completely healed.
He's a very affectionate boy who really doesn't ask for a lot, but he sure does like belly rubs and cuddle sessions. He enjoys every meal, and loves the raw bone-in treats that we give him every day. He's content to make himself comfortable on his big cushy bed, and will alert to sounds that he's not familiar with. We always announce ourselves when we greet RJ, and he always has a nose to the air - his other senses take over for his lack of sight. He knows every bush and tree on his walks, and likes going out for short adventures. He likes car rides, too. We guide him with our voices.
We're searching for an owner that knows that sometimes dogs that aren't perfect CAN be perfect. RJ is always cheerful, gentle and doesn't know a bad day. He learns very fast when taught, too. He greets every day and person with a smile on his face. He's a really amazing spirit.
If you would like to meet this remarkable boy, please complete an application for adoption: www.deafdogrescueofamerica.org/adoption-application.html

animal.description:
Handsome Roscoe is a 2-3 year old, 70-ish double merle Aussie with no obvious hearing or sight impairments.

Roscoe is a very charming and loving boy. He loves to play with other dogs, and he loves to fetch the ball (haven’t tried frisbee yet).  This young dog knows all the tricks -- sit - stay - paw – but he could really use some manners and table etiquette.

He becomes quite possessive over “high value” items (meaning your things, food and bones). He is not typically a chewer when left alone;  However, when seeking your attention - he will grab something he shouldn't have and start chewing.  Roscoe can become dominant – meaning snarling and snapping if he doesn’t want to give up an item, but can be persuaded to trade for another item (food / bone).  This behavior is a work in progress. Roscoe's original owner did not properly establish who was the boss.  He has made some strides, but being challenged is something new to Roscoe. It will take some time to overcome his attitude.
 
Aussies are bred to be brave so they can dominate and control large herds of animals – but they also need to be taught when to turn that behavior off. Aussie's are typically very smart and they learn quickly. Roscoe would do best in a home with herding dog experience.
 
Roscoe has a lot of potential, but needs the right handler. His behavior improves after a good run or romp with another dog. It is recommended that his home have an active playmate even though it may be necessary to feed the dogs separately. 

Roscoe has a strong prey drive – cats or smaller animals might not be a good match. He does seem to be good with dogs of any size.

With his herding instincts, it's best that he go to a home where children are 12 or above.

This poor sweetie tested positive for heartworm and Lyme, but that hasn’t affected his happy personality one bit!  Lyme is a tick borne disease that is not contagious to other dogs or humans but will remain in his system, throughout his life.  Roscoe may have an occasional flare-up which would be indicated by joint pain/inflammation, limping, lethargy and possible loss of appetite.  Typically a dose of antibiotics is enough to make the disease go dormant again.  To help control the Lyme, Roscoe will need a yearly Lyme vaccine.  Should he have multiple flare ups in a short amount of time, his kidneys could be affected.  Lyme has become more prevalent in the southern states, and many dogs with this disease have lived long happy lives!

Heartworm disease is easily preventable with heartworm preventative, which Roscoe unfortunately did not receive from his previous owner.  It is treatable/curable but will take several months to do.  Hence, we're looking for a local foster to adopt home for Roscoe.  HART will cover the cost of his heartworm and initial Lyme treatment but Roscoe would be much more comfortable being in a home instead of boarding at the vet's office.  

If you would be interested in fostering to adopt Roscoe, please go to our website, at www.rescueahart.org, and fill out both a foster and adoption application.

All HART dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped and up to date on all vaccines, including bordatella and rabies.   They are heartworm tested and on preventative for heartworm, fleas, and ticks.   If you are interested in any of our pets, you must complete an online dog adoption application   at www.rescueAhart.org .   The application will put you in touch with this wonderful dog's foster family so you can schedule a meeting.   Thanks!   www.rescueAhart.org

animal.description:
HI!? I’m Benny!
I’m a 2 year old, 50 pound, Pointer mix who’s up-to-date on all shots, neutered and loves attention and playing fetch ? . I could play fetch aaaaaalllll day! If we aren’t playing then I’m good with lounging on the couch with you too. I love attention and being with my people. I’m house trained and crate trained, although I’d rather not be in my crate and I’ll let you know about it for the first few minutes or so I’m in the crate by barking and whining. But I usually settle down. At night I sleep beside or under my foster parents bed, but I would totally love to sleep in bed next to you. I get along with other dogs. I haven’t been around cats ???, so not so sure I’d like them. And children would be new for me too, maybe an older child would be best because sometimes I like to jump and run and I’d hate to knock one over or hurt them. animal.description:
This is Malina!

10-year-old Malina entered the Animal Friends of the Valley as a stray without any identification, and sadly, no one came for her. When the shelter reached out to us about Malina, they described her as "a ball of love" who is great with both dogs and people and just wants to cuddle or roll over for a belly rub. We made Malina a Frosted Face on January 22nd! It seems like she may have some hip or leg issues that could be age-related, but we'll know for sure after Malina goes to our vet soon for an exam, full body x-rays, and bloodwork. This newbie is a full-figured gal at 83 lbs.

Our volunteers and staff are giving Malina lots of love and attention as she settles in to the routine at Frosted Faces.

We will add more information about her

soon, but in the meantime, you can stop by during our next Open House to meet her!

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

animal.description:
Poochie is one of 26 dogs that HCPA was helping to transfer to other rescues.  Unfortunately, before it was her time to leave from her original location, she and another dog got out and the neighbor shot them.  Poochie was lucky, she made it back.  Her partner in crime did not.  After a thorough exam at our vet clinic, it was determined the leg was shattered and she was in extreme pain.  Removal of the leg brought her immediate relief and she has adapted extremely well.  She zooms around the yard and gets around very well.  She is kept inside either in a crate or small enclosure and let outside to potty or longer if the weather permits.  She will bark at strange things when outside but is quiet when inside unless she whines to go outside.  She is learning to ride in a car but still timid about it and generally just lays down until arriving at the destination.  She has never been fond of a leash so still needs some slow training.

She is non-food aggressive with people, dogs or cats.  She should be fine with young children except that she might bump into them as she still learns to navigate around on 3 legs.

Hasn't she got the greatest smile?

animal.description:
Meet Kendall!! She is two years old and just the happiest girl you’ve ever met! She is 60 pounds. She loves loves loves loves people. This poor girl was living in a shelter for 6 months before she finally found rescue. She is adjusting to life in a home and is doing really well. She is crate trained and working on potty training and basic manners. Unfortunately, she tested positive for heartworm and is currently going through treatment - all treatment is covered in her adoption. It will require her to be kept calm for the next 6 months. She’s a pretty calm girl, and doesn’t mind chilling next to you while you’re working or staying on her crate. She’s currently in a foster home with another dog - and she tolerates him, but doesn’t really love him. This may be from her being in a kennel for so long. They coexist fine, but I think she’d be happiest as your only dog. We are cat testing her this week. 

Kendall really just wants someone to give her a chance. She is fine with a house or apartment, and doesn’t require a yard. She prefers to be inside with you any chance she gets. She is VERY CUDDLY- and would sit in your lap and be as close to you as possible if she got the choice. This is an amazing girl - fostered in Denver, Colorado! 

If interested in Kendall please send in an application as the first step. www.soardogs.org

Adoption donation required. This covers altering, DAP series vaccinations to date of adoption, Bordetella Vaccination, Rabies vaccination if over four months, Microchip, Deworming, heartworm test (if over 8 months), monthly flea/heartworm prevention to date, grooming, full veterinary examination, and temperament evaluation. Please e-mail us for more information or go to our website https://soardogs.org/adoption-application for an application. Thank you very much! 


All SOAR dogs go through a ten-day quarantine period to ensure they are healthy, before being adopted. We do not operate on a first come first serve basis, but screen applicants in order to find the best fit for our adoptable dogs.

If you're interested in any of our wonderful dogs, you must FIRST fill out an Adoption Application at our website listed below. Once we receive it, we'll forward it to the foster family for follow up. We are 100% foster based, so we don't have a facility. Review the process FAQ at our website.

Adoption applications can be found here: http://labrescuefresno.org/available-labs/adoption-application/

Adoption Fees Adult Dog (10 mos. - 7 years): $250.00 Puppy (9 mos. and under): $350.00 Senior (8 yrs. and up)/Special Needs Dog: $100.00

Rusty - Yellow Male, Age 1 Year, 80 lbs
If you are ready to ensure that your New Year's Resolution is met, and you are ready for a larger-than-life hunk of love, just in time for Valentine's Day... then look no further than Rusty! He will ensure that you are out of bed every morning ready for a brisk walk, a jog, a sprint, or a marathon!
This bundle of Labrador energy is a healthy, young, 1-year old male that sadly has not had any structure in his one year on earth. He was adopted with good intentions, but he became a backyard dog, and became bored and alone and then too much to handle. We hear this tale all too much, and young Labradors are a real commitment of time, training, structure, and consistency. They also like to be included with their people, and usually have other doggy playmates. Rusty is no different!
So Rusty is putting out his classified ad to find true Labrador lovers before Valentine's Day, he will be ready to meet his forever people.
Rusty's personal ad will read:
Seeking an active home life with a family that will make me a priority. Will need to be a home with lots of exercise, brain games, obedience classes, maybe a personal trainer, and more! I am learning to come indoors, learning to understand what a kennel and a crate are, and meeting new dogs and learning to play and behave like a nice boy. I would like another dog my size to play and romp with. I am ok with kids, but I am a big strong boy that doesn't know how to control my boundless energy, so older children are best. I am not interested in living with cats, I say forget the cats and spend more time with me! I have a strong voice, healthy lungs, and can bark when necessary to let you know my needs... hope you are ready for a big hunk of Labrador if you pick me!
Rusty will require a home that is ready to work with a young dog with boundless energy, muscle, and brawn. He would benefit from a home that will provide boundaries, and work on progression with crate training, indoor time, play manners, leash skills, and more. He is not recommended for a 'first time' dog family, as he is a strong big boy with a lot of power.
If your New Year's resolution is to spend more time outside, hiking, biking, running, walking, and looking for a companion that can log some miles with you, and would love to be your companion, then apply for Rusty! A training plan and commitment for obedience work is a must for this boy!

Apply at www.labrescuefresno.org, applicants will be screened and responded to accordingly. Dogs are adopted out based on their needs, not a first come process, please be patient with our volunteers as they respond to applicants.
If you are interested in adopting through Labrador Retriever Rescue of Fresno, you must first fill out an Adoption Application located at our website www.LabRescueFresno.org All dogs are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccines including rabies; flea/tick topical drops, heartworm tested and microchipped. Thank you for opting to adopt!!
Adoption FeesAdult Dog (10 mos. - 7 years): $250.00 Puppy (9 mos. and under): $350.00Senior (8 yrs. and up)/Special Needs Dog: $100.00

animal.description:
REX IS LOCATED IN SALT LAKE CITY UTAH

Hiya! !My name is Rex. I'm a 4 year old, black and tan short haired dachshund. I am neutered and housebroke. My owners were allergic and could no longer care for me.

The nice people at DRUT found me a foster family to help me work on my socialization issues. At first I was really nervous to meet the other dogs and barked and growled at them alot. Now I realize the other dogs are pretty cool. I can't say much for the cat at the moment. I have only met him a couple times, he keeps on running away and hissing when I chase him.

Anyway I have really enjoyed exploring the yard at my foster's home and would like to live in a home with a fully fenced yard. I do require a sweater or jacket when I'm out, I do not enjoy being cold. I'm very sweet and love head scratches and cuddles.I would love to cuddle up with the family on the couch for a family movie night. I like to sleep in a dog bed on the floor next to your bed at night. I could be left out when you're not home or in a kennel. Yes, I will bark and cry when you leave, however it's only because I miss you so much. I just thought you should know just in case you share walls with neighbors, I can be pretty loud.

I am very loyal and will love you and your family forever. I love being around adults & kids and enjoy meeting new people. I can't promise that I won't be nervous around new dogs, however I will try my best. If you are interested in me please submit an application.

https://www.dachshundrescueoflosangeles.com/applications/adoption-application/

animal.description:
If you could see Piglet's adorable pink round belly, you'd know why she wears her barnyard moniker with pride!   

This lovely little girl, estimated to be 8-10 years of age, was left at a shelter when her original owner did not want to pay for surgery to repair a torn ACL.  Piglet's ACL has now been repaired and she is just waiting for the perfect "forever home".
 
PLEASE READ THE FOLLOWING IN ITS ENTIRELTY TO SEE IF PIGLET COULD BE A GOOD MATCH FOR YOU. 

Piglet would be a wonderful companion for a retired person or "work from home" dog parents who want to make a sweet terrier a part of their daily life.   She would be fine with another small, calm canine sibling although we suspect she'd relish being the center of attention.  

Piglet is completely housebroken and rarely barks.   She is very affectionate and loves being with her people.  She enjoys short walks and has never met a stuffed toy she didn't like.  

Piglet's future home must be one that is committed to exceptional veterinary care as she may require physical therapy, laser therapy or even accupuncture for her surgical leg.  Piglet is also a bit "porky" (you'll pardon the pun) and like so many of us this time of year, she needs to stay on a healthy diet!
 
If you are interested in adoption, you will find out application at http://www.cairnrescueusa.com/.../www.../adopt/frm_adopt.php.  

We do not match dogs on a "first come, first served" basis; rather we strive to make the best match for each dog.  Out of state applicants are welcomed, however, once approved for adoption it is the responsibility of the adopting family to travel to the foster home.

Piglet is UTD on all shots, spayed and microchipped.

animal.description:
Apply on our adoption application at leadrescue.org. We do not adopt out of state. We only adopt in Illinois and within Illinois, 50 miles from downtown Chicago.

Instead of waking up to singing the theme song of One Saturday Morning and all the cartoons that I hope most of my generation remembers, I get to wake up to the “rescue song”:

“I have a friend whose friend’s daughter can’t keep her dog.”
“Just surrendered at the shelter for being a puppy.”
“Owner wasn’t expecting it to have this much energy.”
“It’s old, so they don’t want it anymore.”
“I found a dog, what do I do next? Can you take it?”
32 Facebook tags/notifications

And these aren’t even messages from the fosters who have our dogs in LEAD. I really love not waking up to an emergency lol. But even though this can be a lot for the average person, I signed up for this when all I wanted to do was save some helpless doggos. I just didn’t think it’d go so far, so fast.

While my 4 month old son was practicing the most dreaded infant task-tummy time-I was messaged about a 5 month old Pittie Beagle mix. She was found by a family, kept for 2 months, and eventually they realized they couldn’t do it in the long run. So they brought her to the shelter, where we felt if she got to stay 2 months out of there, we couldn’t let her sit another 2 months wondering what’s going on. I sent the hold immediately and resumed my son’s torture.

“Catch her if you can, Pepper Ann” because I have a feeling she won’t last long. Pepper Ann is as Taylor Swift would call, a Lover. She is a growing 34 lb pup who loves cats, dogs, and kids, filled with happiness, playfulness, and cuddles. She loves to play tug of war but settles nicely when the war tugging concedes. Although she despises the crate and doesn’t really understand that the grass or yellow snow isn’t just for show, we know she’s a smart girl who will catch onto pottying outside with the right teacher. Her best bet would be to have a home with a yard to let her out as often as potty training takes but if you prove to us you don’t mind having to bundle yourself up, getting all sweaty in your puffy coat and putting on her booties cuz the salt on doggie paws freaking sucks, at least 10 times a day, an apartment might be ok. Or an apartment with a dog run might be the real ticket seeing how there’s like a million pee smells just doused in the grass.

Pepper Ann is, in our eyes, so lucky. Yeah sure she whines and barks in the crate and isn’t fully potty trained. But when a 5 month old puppy is HAPPY, excited to meet people and other animals, and doesn’t seem to be scared of her own shadow, it means she hasn’t lived a bad life so far. She wasn’t tainted by the terrible things many other dogs have gone through. Pepper only knows good and positivity, which like my son, only knows too. To him, I’m the best thing in the world...besides his bottle. We want Pepper Ann to stay innocent forever.

If you are interested in adopting a dog another family unfortunately couldn’t keep but that means you get to shoot your shot, please apply for Pepper Ann at leadrescue.org!

animal.description:
Apply to foster or adopt at leadrescue.org. We only foster and adopt in Illinois and within 60 miles of downtown Chicago. 

In need of a foster or foster to adopt for Wonton. 

-Very dog friendly! Pretty playful and excitable and will do great with another fun dog. Would be a great dog park dog!
-Deaf but it doesn’t stop him!
-Very treat and toy motivated so training him while he is deaf should be easy.
-Not fully housebroken but goes out every 3-4 hours. Can hold it overnight.
-Hates the crate but can put him in there while out.
-Can be a bit mouthy but he is a 1 year old puppy who can easily be distracted by his obsession with toys and treats!
-Sweet and friendly.

*******************************************
Deaf dogs can do anything hearing dogs can do, except hear. 

Captain Obvious, sit down.

When we are looking to add dogs into LEAD, we do have criteria. Primarily, do we have a foster and dog friendly? There is a much longer list that will bore you, but those are mainly the points we need to make sure we align.

What struck us about Wonton were 3 things. First, this is a face more than a mother could love. He is definitely going to be the dog people ask what he is mixed with which if you love talking about your dog already, add Wonton to your life. Secondly, he’s fun size with Bassett Hound like paws and a can do attitude. He loves a good time even when everything is closed. Wonton finds the sun at the end of the rainbow. And lastly, he is deaf! Those big floppy doppy, droopies hide his only secret.

We do not view deafness as a bad thing or any reason to not take on a dog. In fact my own dog, Tum Tum-a LEADer alum-is also partially deaf...or better yet selective hearing especially when she’s being a bit naughty. His handling video showed him to be goofy, spunky, and absolutely in love with every dog he met. So putting everything together, we took this lover boy.

Wonton is some kind of 1.5 year old Lab/Pit/Beagle mix and we are looking for someone to FOSTER or ADOPT him. We would love someone who has read up on hand signal training and a pocketful of treats or a basket of toys ready to be demolished. This dog is so food and toy motivated, we see no reason why Wonton couldn’t learn. He even throws his own toys in the air because he just can’t get enough. These both will be helpful in his jumpiness and puppy mouthiness. Better yet, if you also have a playful dog who needs a buddy going at the same speed, Wonton is DOWN.

Even though he can’t hear, Wonton is not at all skittish. But with anyone hard of hearing, it does take patience to get their attention. I say if he is sleeping, put a treat by his nose and he’ll wake up easily and happy! Wonton, although deaf, he can howl/whine/bark and he does so in the crate. So either you don’t crate him or you live in a single family home where that won’t bother anyone. He is still young, so for housebreaking, he goes out every 3-4 hours but can hold it overnight! Just don’t wait too long or he’ll leave you an expected surprise.

Overall, Wonton doesn’t let his situation make or break him. He doesn’t know you can hear, so he just thinks this world is pretty damn peaceful! And hey, we all like some peace and quiet RIGHT NOW! If you are interested in fostering, fostering to adopt, or adopting Wonton, please apply at leadrescue.org.

animal.description:
Foster needed! Please read entire ad

DJ came to us after being adopted and returned to animal services. He is a happy guy who is currently 3-4 months old (still has his puppy toofers!) and 35lbs. He’s shy but loves his humans and is a cuddle bug. You can tell that he has not had a lot of social interaction but he does warm up and is relatively submissive with other dogs. Because of his lack of socialization, DJ has learned some early resource guarding. While great with kids/other dogs 95% of the time, he protects his things, including your bed if he is allowed up (growling, no incidents of biting). He will lunge at other dogs to drive them away. Since he is so young, this is easily and quickly fixed, he just needs to learn that he does not get to make the decisions and if he claims something, he loses it. We have already seen improvement in the few days we’ve had him. We are looking for a foster home that can help this wayward young laddie go from a sweet, submissive boy 95% of the time to one 100% of the time. If you are interested in fostering, we do require you to be local to the DFW area, have a house with a fenced yard, where he will be an inside dog and won’t be left alone for long hours. While we think he will eventually be wonderful with kids, we need a house with no kids under 12 until we can trust him completely. One by One Pet Rescue is a Flower Mound based 501c3

Observations with Cats: Not good with cats
Observations with Kids: Not yet tested
Currently Living at: Foster Home in the DMV area

Hi! I'm Bobby (otherwise known as Robert, Mr. B, or Bob for short). Check out my instagram page: https://www.instagram.com/boop_its_bobby/

Bobby is a gorgeous, black, and white Siberian Husky. This 3-year-old fluffy boy weighs 75lbs. He was rescued from a shelter in PG County, Maryland. Bobby is food-motivated and smart and already knows several commands including ""paw"". He enjoys being close to humans and is social and outgoing. Making new friends is one of Bobby's favorite things to do and he's generally a happy-go-lucky kind of guy. He is currently being fostered in the city and loves going out to explore, sniff, and see who's out and about. Unlike some huskies we've met, Bobby hasn't proved to be overly vocal so far and is not a big barker. 

True to the husky temperament, Bobby is strong and athletic. He loves being outdoors and would make a perfect hiking or running buddy. The cold weather doesn't bother Bobby one bit and seems to put him in a very good mood - after all, his breed hails from Siberia! He needs lots of exercise and would thrive with an adopter who would run with him or give him off-leash playtime in a yard or a dog park. In turn, he will help you to stay fit and will snuggle up next to you while you work or watch TV. 

Like most shelter dogs, Bobby may need a refresher on housetraining and crate training. We ask all of DC PAWS' fosters to work on both house and crate training with their foster dog. Bobby is a confident boy and needs a proper intro to new dogs. With a good introduction, he seems to do well with dog friends. He cannot live in a home with cats or small animals, however, because like many huskies, he has shown that he has a prey drive.

The adoption fee for this dog is $350. If you are interested in adopting Bobby, please submit an adoption application at http://dcpawsrescue.org/adoption-info/.ABOUT US & IMPORTANT DISCLOSURES:

Please note that you must use our official adoption application in order to be considered for adoption. Applying through other sites (i.e., Petfinder) will not work. The following are our applications:

Dog application: https://service.sheltermanager.com/asmservice?account=bg0781&method=online_form_html&formid=1
Cat application: https://service.sheltermanager.com/asmservice?account=bg0781&method=online_form_html&formid=6

DC PAWS Rescue does our best to provide accurate and complete information about our adoptable animals. Please note that we cannot make any guarantees about age or breed; we rely upon our rescue partners and their veterinarians to make those assessments. We also cannot make any guarantees about housebreaking and animal temperament, as animals can behave differently through transition and in different environments.

Our shelter partners provide a basic vet screening for each animal we rescue, which includes necessary vaccinations, deworming, microchipping, and spay/neuter (unless the animal is too young or otherwise deemed by the vet to not be a good candidate for surgery). Please note that this is not a comprehensive medical exam and as such, may not identify any and all medical issues, though our goal is to flag any obvious health issues through the basic vet screening. We share all medical records with adopters and are completely transparent about any known issues prior to adoption finalization. 

ABOUT DC PAWS RESCUE

Our rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based dog and cat rescue in the DC area. We rescue locally from Prince Georges County, MD, and from rural shelters in the south (presently Pickens County, Anderson County, and Greenville County in SC, and Raleigh County, WV).

We partner with a local rescuer in Pickens County, SC, who saves adoptable cats and dogs from the three area shelters. For the animals in this rural area, rescue is a critical lifeline, and often the only lifeline. Our rescue partner not only works with DC PAWS to save as many dogs and cats as possible, but she has also established a successful spay/neuter program in the community to decrease the number of homeless and unwanted animals over the long term.

FOSTER AN ANIMAL IN NEED

Fosters make it possible for DC PAWS to save and care for homeless, neglected and abandoned animals! To learn about fostering dogs or cats for DC PAWS Rescue, please visit: http://dcpawsrescue.org/volunteer/fostering/foster-application

SPONSOR AN ANIMAL IN NEED

For any of our animals! Sponsors help us provide critical medical care, food, boarding, and other support for animals facing euthanasia. Individuals who sponsor a dog or cat receive special recognition on the animal's profile. Sponsorships can also be made in honor or memory of a loved one, and you may designate to whom DC PAWS Rescue should provide notice of your gift. Sponsorship levels of $250 and $150 include ""naming rights"" for a future dog or cat (respectively) that we rescue.

To learn more about sponsorship, please visit: http://dcpawsrescue.org/donate/

animal.description:
I just rescued this sweetheart from the Shelter. New pictures & a more detailed Adoption Profile will be posted in the future as I get to know this dog. Please do not e-mail asking additional questions about this pet. I will update this dogs' Adoption Profile as I am able to assess this dog and know more about this dog if this pet is not adopted beforehand. 

My Rescue does specialize in rescuing abused or neglected pets, so most have some fear issues. Especially of new people...
 
I post updates on the pets in the comment section on each pets' post in our Facebook group. To see his/her progress, go to: https://www.facebook.com/groups/1405138936478168/

Adoption includes:
- Initial Vet check
- Spay/Neuter surgery
- Up to date on Vaccinations 
- Microchip 
- Voucher for a future Free office visit to the Vet
- 50% off any Optimum Wellness Plan
- 30 days of free pet insurance (in case something comes up after adoption)
- Collar 
- Harness *
- Leash
- Other surprise goodies from Safe Haven
- Other coupons from Partners
- Available Paperwork: Spay/Neuter records, Vaccination records, Vet records, Micro records, etc...
- Continued Support: Safe Haven will be there for the lifetime of your new adopted pet. If you ever have questions or concerns, we will always be there to help. Our goal is for you & your pet to live happily ever after! 

PLEASE NOTE: All of the pets at Safe Haven receive basic training when they come to us. What each pet learns depends on how much time I have had to work with them, & if that pet has any additional issues that need to be focused on first.
 

ADOPTING A CAT OR DOG IS UP TO A 20 YEAR COMMITMENT! THEY ARE NOT OBJECTS THAT YOU CAN GET RID OF WHEN THEY BECOME INCONVENIENT. THEY ARE INNOCENT LIVING, BREATHING ANIMALS WITH FEELINGS THAT DEPEND ON YOU TO TAKE CARE OF THEM. IF YOU ARE NOT WILLING TO TAKE CARE OF, LOVE, & PAY FOR EVERYTHING THIS PET NEEDS FOR UP TO 20 YEARS, THEN PLEASE DO NOT ASK FOR AN APPLICATION.


* Safe Haven STRONGLY believes that collars should only be used to hold their ID or as decoration. A dog can slip out of collar. Which becomes a problem if you are trying to restrain your dog, & it comes off. Also, attaching a leash to a collar puts pressure on the neck, which is one of the most delicate areas of the body, & could hurt them. For these reasons, Safe Haven includes a harness with every dog adoption to ensure the safety of the dog. A harness distributes the weight on the chest & shoulders. It also has a handle on the back that you can grab if need be, without hurting your pet (EX: Dog falls off your boat, just grab the handle & pull your pet back in with no harm done. With a collar, you would have to strangle your dog when pulling your dog in). Also, a dog cannot slip out of a harness if it is fitted correctly, so it is much easier to restrain them.


*******
 
FAQ: 
Q: Is this pet still available?
A: The Adoption Profiles are taken down the same day the pet is adopted. So if you see this pet posted, this pet is still available. The only exception is our Facebook page where the profile stays up, and the pets are tagged as "Adopted". Updates are also posted in the comment section of each pets' individual post on our Facebook page for Safe Haven Animal Rescue of AZ at  https://www.facebook.com/groups/1405138936478168/  .Once on the Facebook page, you can type the pets name in the search box to easily pull up all the posts on that pet.

 
Q: I don't see a phone #. Will someone please call me?
A: Everything needed is online. I have found that online is the most efficient way to get all the work done. In the past, when I posted my #, my phone rang off the hook all day. So I spent the whole day on the phone, with not much work to show for it at the end of the day. Again, everything needed is online.
 
Q: How do I adopt this pet?
A: Your first step is to fill out an application. Please e-mail and ask for one at Safe_Haven_Animal_Rescue@live.com  
 
Q: Where is this pet?  
A:  This pet is being fostered in a private home.
 
Q: I like what you are doing & would like to help. Would you be open to a partnership?
A: Absolutely! I am open to anything that helps care for the animals &/or saves more lives! Please e-mail me at Safe_Haven_Animal_Rescue@live.com and give me details about what you have in mind.
 
Q: How do I become a Sponsor?
A: Thank you! Taking care of each pet gets expensive, and we are so grateful for any monthly donation towards the Vet care, food, treats, toys, ect...
 To become a Sponsor, please click on this link https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&hosted_button_id=6DRAYJN5XEDZ2  You can pay with your PayPal account, or you can pay with a credit card. Once you send in your first invoice, you will automatically get monthly invoices until you choose to cancel. Sponsors get inside knowledge and extra privileges as a thank you for supporting our Rescue efforts!

animal.description:
Wilson is a friendly, affectionate, happy go lucky guy looking to find his new home. He is house trained, walks nicely on the leash and loves to accompany you for a car ride. A curious, gentle, and kinda goofy guy, Wilson just loves hanging out with you and being part of the family.

He loves to play with toys, especially plush stuffies, and enjoys a game of fetch. He's playful and silly, but he is also quite low energy and quiet around the house.

Wilson, like a lot of dogs, LOVES food and treats. He is a smart guy and you can see his little mind always working, trying to figure out what you want him to do. We're sure with patience and treats, you could work with Wilson to help make him an even better version of himself.

Wilson has what his foster mom calls his "happy feet" - he does an adorable little dance whenever she comes home, or gives him a treat. His foster mom tells us he is genuinely a happy dog that has so much life and love in him. Anyone would be lucky to have this guy be a part of their home. He wants affection, he wants love, and he wants to be a part of someone's life.

Wilson is 4 years old, 63 lbs, and ready for his forever home. Please visit www.liveloveanimalrescue.org to fill out an adoption application.

animal.description:
MEET HOWIE!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. He is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4522600.

Howie is a shy guy until he gets to know you and then he will come up to you for pets and lovin'. Howie was brought to the shelter by a good samaritan who said he is crate trained and went right to sleep after he got into the crate. He likes to ride in the car and he did well with the finder's two dogs in the home. Howie has done well on a leash and he likes to go to the play yard and explore. He did well when introduced to other dogs but he does get startled easily and will bark at another dog if he gets startled. He loves to wag his tail when he's happy.

Howie came into the shelter with skin conditions and needs to see a full service vet to determine what he needs to get healthy. He can sometimes appear insecure and just needs to gain his confidence with a great adopter in a new home. If you can help Howie and give him the attention and love that he needs in a new home, please bring the family and come and meet him today! If you have any dogs at home now, please bring them with you to meet Howie.

If you are interested in saving this pet, please reach out via this link: https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/foster/BPAZ/Dog

To actually visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show, and we have seen that you can generally show up and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog and the shelter will squeeze you in, except from 12-3PM or closer to the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

animal.description:
MEET TOBY!

Toby is approx 2 years old, he is currently in boarding waiting for his forever home. Toby likes to play with toys, loves to go on walks, he walks great on the leash. He makes the best Hiking/Walking/Jogging buddy!!!! Toby is looking for a home that will continue to work with him to be the best dog he can be. He needs to have a home with a backyard. Toby needs to be your ONE and ONLY PET in the home......he is friendly, loving and a goofy boy!

Read about my day foster trip with my volunteer friend::

OMG! I was so excited that my friend was taking me out on an adventure trip. She picked me up, and I jumped right into the car, and off we went. She says I ride very well in the car, love to stick my head out the window. Our first stop was Papago Park, I jumped out of the car, and off we went. I was taking in all the smells. I walk really well on the leash, I didn't react to other dogs, I didn't care about the ducks either. People riding bikes, skateboards didn't bother me either. We saw lots of people with dogs and kids, it was really exciting! We walked up mountains, came across water, didn't care for the water much. Later another friend met up with her day foster doggie, and we all continued to walk all over the place. It was a long fun 7 miles. My friend says I'm the perfect hiking/walking/jogging buddy!! I hope my new family will enjoy these fun adventures too.

Our next stop was a yummy place called McDonalds. I got a special treat, a plain hamburger and a ice cream cone, it was so yummy!!! Then it was time to head back to boarding. I don't handle the boarding place very well, it stresses me out. I would really love to have my own family to love me and I can love them back. Will that be you??

No apartments/condo/townhomes

If you are interested in meeting this dog, please visit our website for our online application www.underdogaz.com. He is with Freedom Brothers Rescue, but you can fill out the application on this site. Feel free to text 480-359-7109 with questions.

PLEASE NOTE: This dog is courtesy posted for another individual or Rescue. Different policies and fees may apply.

animal.description:
Jax is an approximate 8 year old mixed breed fella!   Sadly,  Jax joined us after his person passed away.  Jax took it real hard.  He didn't eat for days.  His world has been turned upside down.  Poor baby!

When Jax was adopted, his owner was told he was a pit/weimaraner mix.  We are thinking that he looks dane or greyhound to us!  When he runs, his ears go back.  He is such an aerodynamic fella!  

We received a bit of information from Jax's previous owner.  We were told that Jax is protective of his person, especially in small spaces and the home but easily makes friends otherwise.  Jax needs exercise.  A fenced in area to run would be great.  Jax is extremely intelligent and would really like a job if you are hiring.  If he doesn't have one, he takes to sorting trash.  Gross!  Someone has to do it!

We learned that Jax sits funny for treats.  His 'sit' is like a little back leg hop.   It is so cute that the volunteers just can't resist giving this boy extra treats!  If you stop petting Jax, he will let you know by inserting himself under your hand.  Jax has never lived with another dog, but appears to want to play with some of the other rescue pups.  His former person never trusted him around cats.  Jax would probably do best in a home without kiddos or other pets.  

If you are interested in learning more about this fine fella, please visit our website, www.crcpa.org, and complete an application!  Jax is waiting for you!

animal.description:
*PLEASE NOTE: ADOPTERS INTERESTED IN THIS LITTER MUST HAVE DOG EXPERIENCE & A YARD*

Raina is an 8 week old female catahoula/pit bull mix puppy who weighs about 5 lbs. This litter of puppies was rescued from an overcrowded high kill shelter after being dumped when they were only 6 weeks old. Our hearts broke for these tiny babies - a loud, scary shelter is no place to grow up! We feel lucky to have the chance to provide these pups with a safe place to land. Have you seen a prettier bunch?? They have the most gorgeous and unique markings. These babies are very shy at first, but who could blame them after what they've been through? Patience and gentleness will be required to make them feel comfortable as they learn they are safe. These babies seem incredibly intelligent and high energy, so we are looking for experienced homes with yards for them to thrive and grow. Families will need to be prepared to feel little baby puppy teeth against their fingers and toes thanks to these little pipsqueaks... at least they are adorable! They will need proper training, socializing, and lots of love in order to grow into the loyal, well-mannered companions they are meant to be. This bunch loves to wrestle together, then curl up in a big puppy pile for a nap. We just adore their wrinkly faces and cannot wait to watch them flourish with their forever families. Please help us find these pups the forever homes they deserve!

Interested in adopting? Take the first step and complete an adoption application on our website: https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/
We are a foster based organization, so we do not have a facility to visit. Please read our FAQs to learn more: https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/faq
Follow us on Facebook for foster updates and a full list of our adoptable pets: https://www.facebook.com/all4pawsrescue/

animal.description:
This charming little guy is 8 year old Alby and depending on how you look at him, you could say retriever or you could say dachshund but we'll sum him up as totally adorable. We actually have no idea what his breeds are, but those are our best guesses.

He joined an Ontario shelter when his family no longer wanted to care for him,  but he went on a hunger strike while in the shelter, so being the compassionate shelter they are, he went home with one of their staff members to be fostered. 

Then love happened, for both of them.  Kindred spirits. But alas, the felines of the family revolted and as all good things often do, this love affair had to end. 

So, we welcomed 24 pound Alby to Mattie's Place.

He's a character this one. He loves to eat "stuff". Whatever he can hork down his throat, he will. That's what landed him in the shelter. A tussel to get something out of his mouth resulted in a bite to his owner.

He doesn't however guard items.  He just tries to eat things, and isn't happiest about giving them up.  It sounds like guarding, but big picture is, it isn't, as it's only occasional items he wants to eat.

He dislikes, strongly ....  Dogs. Cats. Kibble. Vets. 

He loves, strongly ... Cuddles. People. Walks. Snow. Car rides. 

Who's perfect? He's not. But neither am I, so we can't judge. 

He occasionally limps on his left hind leg.  The shelter vet and our vet couldn't find a reason why and it seems to not bother him beyond an occasional mild favouring. His front legs have "out toeing" which could be elbow dysplasia, as his legs are very short and squat and typical of a dachshund disposition.  His front legs do not pose any issue for him, but he does have a weird little skip, hop, limp on the one right leg.  It's not anything we would do surgery on, as we don't see it as a difficulty for him, but should it become an issue down the road, but would not be covered under insurance, as it's noted in his records and will be pre-existing, so keep that in mind if adopting. His back leg is not noted in his records anywhere. 

We know we'll find forever people for him to cuddle soon. It might even be you reading this, that Alby is waiting for!

No kids. No dogs. No cats.  Hard no's and non negotiable.  He's also not a dog for a first time dog owner.  He's an amazing boy, but you need to bring experience to the table to adopt Alby,

A country home where he doesn't have to run into other dogs would be best, as the sight of other dogs really stresses him out and he is incredibly vocal and reactive when seeing them and meeting them would likely not go well.

He gets very vocal when he's displeased (check out the video in his profile) or when he encounters another dog, so avoidance for now is the best option for Alby.

He would do best working with a professional trainer to help him overcome this reactivity and overall anxiety.  

He's also not a fan of being alone, and can exhibit anxiety, so a home where someone is there with him most of the the time is the best scenario for Alby, to keep him as happy as he can be.

The shelter had him medicated for his stay with them, because of his stress levels being so high, but he does much better once settled into a home and we haven't had to medicate him at all in foster care with us at Mattie's Place.

___________________________________

FROM HIS FOSTER MOM & DAD:

Alby is long and short and positively adorable. 

Alby loves pets, walks, and cuddles on the couch. 

He is the most loving dog, always looking to sit on your lap or lie at your feet.  

Alby walks with a slight limp on his front leg, but it doesn’t seem to get in his way. 

He enjoys long walks, but is not such a fan of the other dogs he meets on his walks! 

He will growl and bark at most dogs and requires a tight hold on his leash in these moments. He gets a little overwhelmed when walking on busy streets.

Alby likes things his way! When we got Alby, he would only eat cooked patties during meal times. We have since begun to mix his kibble with the cooked patties and he now enjoys both. We put his food on a plate because he doesn’t seem to enjoy it when it’s in a dog bowl. Like I said - diva! 

Alby also dislikes being manipulated in any way. If he does not want to do something, he may growl and flash his teeth. He has, however, never nipped either of us and has only done this when we tried to lift him up. He gives clear warnings when he is upset and immediately gives you cuddles right after. 

We are not adopting Alby, only because we cannot sustain a lifestyle of being home all day and giving him all the attention he deserves in the future. 

He deserves a quiet home with a family who will show him the same amount of love he has shown us! 

His adopters will fall in love with him instantly, just as we have. 

We love Alby a ton and hope he finds a forever home that is as special as he is. The fact that we teared up while writing this just says it all :) 
___________________________________

____________________________________________

As of today, though our protocols could change tomorrow, we are still moving forward with adoptions. Our process has changed from some of the previous elements: We are a registered animal welfare organization, so we are deemed an essential service.

All paperwork completed online, video home visits, meet and greets outside respecting social distancing, leashes/collars/supplies wiped down and disinfected (GermiCide 3 wipes), disinfectant on the dog prior to handoff (Aqueos wipes for dogs)

-----------------------

To note: the above description is relevant to this dog in his current & previous setting. Home changes & adopter personalities can bring out different behaviours not previously seen.

We do not specifically kid/cat test our dogs when they arrive at Mattie's Place. That just wouldn't be fair to the dog or child/cat.

We also do not claim, endorse, suggest or hint at, that any of our dogs are hypoallergenic, low shed or no-shed.

Adoption fee includes: spay/neuter, deworming, defleaing, vaccinations, nose to tail health exam, leash|collar, 6 months of preventative based on season/need, DNA test for entertainment purposes, dishes, poop bags, food and any extras she has accumulated in foster care.

animal.description:
I just rescued this sweetheart from the Shelter. New pictures & a more detailed Adoption Profile will be posted in the future as I get to know this dog. Please do not e-mail asking additional questions about this pet. I will update this dogs' Adoption Profile as I am able to assess this dog and know more about this dog if this pet is not adopted beforehand. 

My Rescue does specialize in rescuing abused or neglected pets, so most have some fear issues. Especially of new people...
 
I post updates on the pets in the comment section on each pets' post in our Facebook group. To see his/her progress, go to: https://www.facebook.com/groups/1405138936478168/

Adoption includes:
- Initial Vet check
- Spay/Neuter surgery
- Up to date on Vaccinations 
- Microchip 
- Voucher for a future Free office visit to the Vet
- 50% off any Optimum Wellness Plan
- 30 days of free pet insurance (in case something comes up after adoption)
- Collar 
- Harness *
- Leash
- Other surprise goodies from Safe Haven
- Other coupons from Partners
- Available Paperwork: Spay/Neuter records, Vaccination records, Vet records, Micro records, etc...
- Continued Support: Safe Haven will be there for the lifetime of your new adopted pet. If you ever have questions or concerns, we will always be there to help. Our goal is for you & your pet to live happily ever after! 

PLEASE NOTE: All of the pets at Safe Haven receive basic training when they come to us. What each pet learns depends on how much time I have had to work with them, & if that pet has any additional issues that need to be focused on first.
 

ADOPTING A CAT OR DOG IS UP TO A 20 YEAR COMMITMENT! THEY ARE NOT OBJECTS THAT YOU CAN GET RID OF WHEN THEY BECOME INCONVENIENT. THEY ARE INNOCENT LIVING, BREATHING ANIMALS WITH FEELINGS THAT DEPEND ON YOU TO TAKE CARE OF THEM. IF YOU ARE NOT WILLING TO TAKE CARE OF, LOVE, & PAY FOR EVERYTHING THIS PET NEEDS FOR UP TO 20 YEARS, THEN PLEASE DO NOT ASK FOR AN APPLICATION.


* Safe Haven STRONGLY believes that collars should only be used to hold their ID or as decoration. A dog can slip out of collar. Which becomes a problem if you are trying to restrain your dog, & it comes off. Also, attaching a leash to a collar puts pressure on the neck, which is one of the most delicate areas of the body, & could hurt them. For these reasons, Safe Haven includes a harness with every dog adoption to ensure the safety of the dog. A harness distributes the weight on the chest & shoulders. It also has a handle on the back that you can grab if need be, without hurting your pet (EX: Dog falls off your boat, just grab the handle & pull your pet back in with no harm done. With a collar, you would have to strangle your dog when pulling your dog in). Also, a dog cannot slip out of a harness if it is fitted correctly, so it is much easier to restrain them.


*******
 
FAQ: 
Q: Is this pet still available?
A: The Adoption Profiles are taken down the same day the pet is adopted. So if you see this pet posted, this pet is still available. The only exception is our Facebook page where the profile stays up, and the pets are tagged as "Adopted". Updates are also posted in the comment section of each pets' individual post on our Facebook page for Safe Haven Animal Rescue of AZ at  https://www.facebook.com/groups/1405138936478168/  .Once on the Facebook page, you can type the pets name in the search box to easily pull up all the posts on that pet.

 
Q: I don't see a phone #. Will someone please call me?
A: Everything needed is online. I have found that online is the most efficient way to get all the work done. In the past, when I posted my #, my phone rang off the hook all day. So I spent the whole day on the phone, with not much work to show for it at the end of the day. Again, everything needed is online.
 
Q: How do I adopt this pet?
A: Your first step is to fill out an application. Please e-mail and ask for one at Safe_Haven_Animal_Rescue@live.com  
 
Q: Where is this pet?  
A:  This pet is being fostered in a private home.
 
Q: I like what you are doing & would like to help. Would you be open to a partnership?
A: Absolutely! I am open to anything that helps care for the animals &/or saves more lives! Please e-mail me at Safe_Haven_Animal_Rescue@live.com and give me details about what you have in mind.
 
Q: How do I become a Sponsor?
A: Thank you! Taking care of each pet gets expensive, and we are so grateful for any monthly donation towards the Vet care, food, treats, toys, ect...
 To become a Sponsor, please click on this link https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_s-xclick&hosted_button_id=6DRAYJN5XEDZ2  You can pay with your PayPal account, or you can pay with a credit card. Once you send in your first invoice, you will automatically get monthly invoices until you choose to cancel. Sponsors get inside knowledge and extra privileges as a thank you for supporting our Rescue efforts!

animal.description:
MEET WEDNESDAY!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. She is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4526530.

Wednesday is a beautiful German Shepherd that is scared and confused and doesn't know why she is at the shelter. She is having difficulty with shelter life but the staff is working with her to socialize her and get her used to people. Right now, she doesn't want to walk on a leash but she does like to explore the play yard. She is still nervous around the kennel staff but they have seen her wag her tail a few times when she was in the yard. She won't take treats from their hand but she will eat them. She's just too nervous right now to get close to anyone.

Wednesday needs a rescue or adopter that understands she needs help with her social skills around people and that she's going to need a lot of time and patience when she gets to a new home. She can't go to a home with small children but she could go to a home with another calm, quiet dog. A dog introduction at the shelter is required. If you can give Wednesday the kind of home that she needs, please come and meet her today!

If you are interested in saving this pet, please reach out via this link: https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/foster/BPAZ/Dog

To actually visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show, and we have seen that you can generally show up and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog and the shelter will squeeze you in, except from 12-3PM or closer to the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.
